result.execSummary:
The defendant Alexander Jeffrey Togstad was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Attempt Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

A.D.A. Isherwood appeared for the state.
Defendant appeared in person with Atty. Jelinski.
The state moves to amend Count 4 to simple battery per Sec. 940.19 (1), Class A. misd.
The defendant enters a plea of no contest to Count 2 as charged and also to amended Count 4.
Pleas accepted by the Court after rights were explained and defendant found guilty on Counts 2 and 4.
The remaining counts were dismissed and read in.
The Count sentences the defendant to 6 months in jail on each count, concurrent,  imposed and stayed. Defendant placed on probation for a period of 1 year on each count, concurrent. 
See file for conditions for probation.
Restitution ordered as a condition of probation, summary provided by A.D.A.  The parties will have 30 days to determine / agree on the amount or a hearing will be scheduled.
Appeal rights were provided.
